<article>
    <h1>UP CLOSE WITH STARS IN NEW WAYS</h1>
    <h2>Be&#xAD;sides so&#xAD;cial me&#xAD;dia, celebri&#xAD;ties are turn&#xAD;ing to per&#xAD;son&#xAD;alised in&#xAD;ter&#xAD;ac&#xAD;tion over video-shar&#xAD;ing plat&#xAD;forms to en&#xAD;gage fans and audiences</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200813/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-13"><time>2020-08-13</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">jan&#xAD;lee@sph.com.sg Jan Lee</span>
    </section>

    <p>Celebri­ties used to ex­clu­sively share their thoughts and feel­ings in in­ter­view ar­ti­cles and meet fans in or­gan­ised, tick­eted set­tings.</p>
    <p>With the rise of so­cial me­dia and the coro­n­avirus pan­demic, things have been chang­ing.</p>
    <p>Stars across the spec­trum, from A-lis­ters to lit­tle-known rook­ies, have their own so­cial me­dia ac­counts where they can in­ter­act with fans more di­rectly.</p>
    <p>But even the usual In­sta­gram posts and sto­ries may not be enough now.</p>
    <p>Ever more per­son­alised and cus­tomised in­ter­ac­tion with fans and audiences over video-shar­ing plat­forms are get­ting in­creas­ingly pop­u­lar.</p>
    <p>This trend has sped up due to the Covid-19 out­break which swept the world this year.</p>
    <p>Mu­si­cians turned to on­line con­certs, ac­tors such as Keanu Reeves of­fered Zoom dates with fans to raise funds for char­ity while vir­tual press con­fer­ences re­placed in­per­son me­dia events.</p>
    <p>Forced into live-stream­ing, Hol­ly­wood will host its first vir­tual ma­jor awards cer­e­mony – the Em­mys – next month, where stars such as ac­tresses Jennifer Anis­ton and Kerry Wash­ing­ton are ex­pected to doll up to at­tend the glitzy event from their liv­ing rooms.</p>
    <p>Live-stream­ing is be­com­ing more pro­fes­sional and, lo­cally, film di­rec­tor Jack Neo will take the reins at a new live-stream­ing app named AMM TV (see other story). AMM is short for Asia Mo­men­tum Me­dia.</p>
    <p>An­other Sin­ga­porean-based com­pany, Au­then­tic Celebrity Ex­pe­ri­ences, is work­ing on boost­ing the fan ex­pe­ri­ence with per­son­al­i­ties send­ing tailored video mes­sages.</p>
    <p>Even dra­mas are of­fer­ing greater au­di­ence en­gage­ment with Tik­Tok re­leas­ing its first im­mer­sive Kdrama se­ries Trap, com­plete with so­cial me­dia ac­counts for the char­ac­ters.</p>
    <p>The trend of tech­nol­ogy fa­cil­i­tat­ing greater in­ter­ac­tion be­tween en­ter­tain­ers and fans is here to stay.</p>

